Most investors typically opt for conventional investments to grow their personal wealth. However, savvy investors are recognizing that ETFs can be used in conjunction with
 ISAs to save and invest tax-efficiently . This combination not only offers the potential for growth but also provides a shield against unnecessary tax burdens, maximizing returns in the long run. For those exploring alternative investment vehicles, here are 5 of the most uncommon yet potentially profitable ETFs currently available in newer market sectors.
  The Best AI & Robotics ETF
  The Global X Artificial Intelligence & Technology ETF is considered to be one of the best ETFs on the market. It was launched in May 2018 and was created to produce investment results corresponding in general to the prices and yields of the Indxx Artificial Intelligence & Big Data Index, which comprises enterprises working in the development and use of AI and Big Data.
  It is a non-diversified fund with a net asset worth of 567.79m USD. The expense ratio of this ETF is 0.68%.
  AI covers many segments, and companies include businesses that have both household names and that are newcomers worldwide. Predictions indicate that the AI market could be worth 300bn USD by 2026.
  The Best Cybersecurity ETF
  The iShares Digital Security UCITS ETF USD is widely regarded as one of the top cyber or digital security ETFs globally. Launched in September 2018, the size of the fund totals 1.38bn GBP and its ongoing charge or expense ratio is 0.40%.
  This ETF has been set up to track the STOXX® Global Digital Security Index. In turn, it tracks companies working in the digital security sector. These companies are engaged in working with, safeguarding and or handling sensitive data and accessing control of secure locations.
  The worldwide cybersecurity market is forecast to be worth more than 345bn USD by 2026. Revenues in this sector are predicted to continue growing by approximately 10% to 13% per annum over the next decade.
  The Best Blockchain & Fintech ETF
  One of the top Blockchain and Fintech ETFs is the Global X Blockchain ETF (BKCH). It was launched in December 2021 and has assets with a total value of 61.96m USD with an expense ratio of 0.50%.
  The Global X Blockchain ETF (BKCH) was formed to invest in businesses that have positioned themselves to reap the rewards from the increased adoption of blockchain technology. These businesses include companies involved in digital asset mining, blockchain and digital asset hardware and transactions, blockchain applications, and blockchain asset digital asset integration. This ETF has been set up to provide investment results that correspond closely to the price as well as the yield performance of the Solactive Blockchain Index.
  In 2022, the global blockchain market had an estimated worth of over 10bn USD. By 2023, it has been suggested that this sector will grow tenfold and be worth in excess of 1.4tn USD.
  The Best Space Exploration ETF
  One of the best Space Exploration ETFs is the Procure Space UCITS ETF. There are GBP and USD versions. Launched in June 2021, the size of the GB fund (a relatively small ETFT domiciled in Ireland) totals 9m GBP, and the expense ratio is 0.75% per annum.
  When launched, the Procure Space UCITS ETF Acc was the only ETF to track the S-Network Procure Space index. It is designed to mirror the performance of the underlying index via full replication (meaning buying all the index constituents). The dividends provided via this ETF are accumulated and reinvested in the same ETF.
  The price has recently bottomed out near its all-time low, but it is starting to rise again. Satellite systems and associated technologies are likely to be a major growth market, as the growth of companies like Uber and Deliveroo demonstrate. GPS is Vital to their success in the same way as satellites are crucial for providing higher bandwidth and coverage in both broadband and telecoms.
  Add to the equation the fact that space tourism and hospitality are becoming closer to grasp with wannabe customers queuing up to boldly go where no man has gone before as costs reduce, and it can be an attractive proposition to investors with a reasonable tolerance towards risk.
  The Best Metaverse ETF
  Metaverse ETFs are one of the most interesting technology sector trends at the moment, and the Roundhill Ball Metaverse ETF (METV) is the leader. It was launched in June 2021 and controls funds worth approximately 382.28m USD. It tracks the Ball Metaverse Index and has an expense ratio of 0.59%.
  METV is a passively managed fund that invests in globally listed equities across various industries relating to what it considers to be the future iteration of today's internet. The stocks are selected by a committee and are weighted in tiers and the 47 holdings include Alphabet (GOOGL), Amazon.com (AMZN), Apple (AAPL), Meta Platforms (META), Microsoft (MSFT), QUALCOMM (QCOM), NVIDIA (NVDA), Roblox (RBLX), Unity Software (U), and Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing (TSM).
  With a CAGR of 45%, the global Metaverse market is expected to grow and be worth over 1.3tn by 2030.

stories.title: TME Daily: In what macro backdrop will stocks work?

stories.body:
Los índices de mercado cerraron en alza el martes antes de dos eventos clave. El Dow Jones Industrial Average subió un 0,4% al cierre, mientras que el S&P 500 registró una ganancia del 0,7% en el mercado de valores hoy. Por su parte, el Nasdaq subió otro 0,5% después de la ganancia del 1,2% del lunes, superando su promedio móvil de 200 días.
Los inversores tienen la mira puesta en el miércoles, cuando se espera el anuncio trimestral de reembolsos del Tesoro. Se espera que los funcionarios del Tesoro den detalles sobre la oferta de deuda de 776 mil millones de dólares para el cuarto trimestre y de 816 mil millones de dólares para el primer trimestre de 2024. El segundo evento, la reunión de la Reserva Federal, debería transcurrir sin contratiempos, ya que se espera que la Fed mantenga las tasas sin cambios por ahora.
 Para el miércoles también se espera el informe de la Encuesta de Ofertas de Empleo y Rotación Laboral, que se espera que muestre una disminución en las vacantes laborales, y los datos de nóminas de ADP para octubre se espera que muestren cambios en el empleo privado.
 Además, los inversores esperan los datos del Índice de Gestores de Compras del Sector Manufacturero y del Índice de Manufacturas del Instituto de Gestión de Suministros, también el miércoles.
 Mientras tanto, los datos publicados el martes mostraron que la confianza del consumidor superó los 100 puntos en octubre, pero disminuyó en comparación con septiembre, según el Conference Board.
 En el NYSE, el volumen fue menor, mientras que en el Nasdaq fue mayor, en comparación con el día lunes. Las pequeñas capitalizaciones impulsaron al índice Russell 2000 en un 0,9%.
 El petróleo crudo cayó aún más, hasta alcanzar los 81,16 dólares por barril. Además, la rentabilidad de la nota del Tesoro a 10 años cayó 1 punto básico al 4,86%.
 El fondo cotizado en bolsa Innovator IBD 50 (FFTY) ganó un 0,4%.
 Bitcoin formó una cruz dorada alcista después del reciente rally en criptomonedas, mientras los inversionistas esperan un fondo cotizado en bolsa de bitcoin. La media móvil de 50 días para el activo criptográfico cruzó la línea de los 200 días, según Cointelegraph.
 Mientras tanto, el fondo cotizado en bolsa Ark Fintech Innovation ETF (ARKF) de Cathie Wood compró 473.225 acciones de la empresa de tecnología financiera Sofi Technologies (SOFI). Sofi cuenta con una plataforma de criptomonedas que respalda varias monedas digitales, incluyendo bitcoin, ethereum, litecoin y otras.
 Acciones del Dow Jones: Apple, Caterpillar
 Apple (AAPL) subió un 0,3% antes de publicar sus resultados del jueves. El gigante tecnológico con sede en Cupertino, California, presentó un nuevo MacBook con el chip M3. Se informa que la versión M3 Max de gama alta es compatible con desarrolladores de inteligencia artificial.
 Caterpillar (CAT) cayó un 6% después de que una perspectiva de ventas en desaceleración compensara un informe sólido del tercer trimestre.
 Fuera de las acciones del Dow Jones, las acciones de Pinterest (PINS) subieron y volvieron a superar la línea de los 50 días después de que el crecimiento de las ventas en el tercer trimestre llegara al 11% y se acelerara por cuarto trimestre consecutivo. Los márgenes más que se duplicaron, llegando al 24% en comparación con el 11% del año pasado. La acción se encuentra en el rango de compra a partir de una entrada en los 28,90 dólares.
 Sin embargo, el líder de chips Lattice Semiconductor (LSCC) informó su quinto trimestre de desaceleración de ventas y ganancias. Las acciones cayeron a mínimos de noviembre.
 Rambus (RMBS) subió más del 10% a medida que las ventas y los ingresos desaceleraron durante dos trimestres consecutivos.
 Wolfspeed (WOLF) también subió entre las acciones impulsadas por los informes de ganancias del primer trimestre fiscal. Para su segundo trimestre, el fabricante de tecnologías de carburo de silicio espera ventas en el punto medio de 207 millones de dólares y una pérdida de 69 centavos por acción. Las acciones subieron un 20%.
 Las acciones de Tesla (TSLA) subieron después de que el fabricante de vehículos eléctricos ganara su primer juicio en el que se alegaba que su función de piloto automático había causado accidentes fatales.
 Fuera del Dow Jones: AMD sube antes de las ganancias
 También fuera del índice Dow Jones, el gigante de los chips Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) subió un 0,2% antes de las ganancias, que se esperaban después del cierre del mercado. Las acciones están por debajo de sus medias móviles clave.
 Cameco (CCJ), una adición reciente a IBD SwingTrader, está recuperándose después de tocar su línea de los 50 días con un fuerte volumen. Las ventas del tercer trimestre del minero de uranio aumentaron un 48%, pero las ganancias se dispararon un 967%.
 En el IBD 50, ELF (ELF) cayó bruscamente por debajo de su línea de los 200 días antes de las ganancias del miércoles, pero Deckers (DECK) mostró una acción impresionante y aumentó sus sólidas ganancias después del informe de resultados.
 Vertiv (VRT) está superando la línea de los 50 días y se acerca a un punto de compra de 40,41 dólares.
 Por favor, siga a VRamakrishnan en X/Twitter para obtener más noticias sobre el mercado de valores hoy.

Market indicators closed on Tuesday before two key events. The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 0.4% at the close, while the S&P 500 recorded a 0.7% gain in the stock market today. For its part, Nasdaq rose another 0.5% after winning 1.2% on Monday, exceeding its average mobile 200-day average.
Investors have the look on Wednesday when the quarterly announcement of Treasury refunds is expected. Treasury officials are expected to provide details on the $776 billion debt offer for the fourth quarter and $816 billion for the first quarter of 2024. The second event, the Federal Reserve meeting, should pass without any precedent, as the Fed is expected to maintain rates without change for now.
The report of the Employment and Labor Survey is also expected for Wednesday, which is expected to show a decline in the number of job vacancies, and ADP numbers for October are expected to show changes in private employment.
In addition, investors expect data from the Manufacturing Sector Procurement Sector Procurement Index and the Manufacturing Index of the Institute of Supply Management, including Wednesday.
Meanwhile, the data published on Tuesday showed that consumer confidence exceeded 100 points in October, but declined compared to September, according to the Conference Board.
In the NYSE, the volume was smaller, while in Nasdaq it was larger than Monday. Small capitalisations pushed the Russell 2000 index at 0.9%.
The crude oil fell even further, to the tune of $81.16 per barrel. In addition, the profitability of the Treasury note to 10 years fell 1 basis point to 4.86%.
The fund quoted in the Innovation IBD 50 (FFTY) stock was 0.4%.
Bitcoin formed an 10th-century cross after the recent sly in cryptodonades, while investors expect a fund quoted in the bag of bitcoin. The 50-day mobile medium for the cryptographic activity crossed the 200-day line, according to Cointelegraph.
Meanwhile, the fund listed in the Ark Fintech Innovation ETF (ARF) by Cathy Wood bought 473,225 shares from the company financial technology company Sofia Technologies (SFI). Sofia has a platform of cryptomedones that supports several digital currencies, including bitcoin, etherea, nitcoin and others.
Dow Jones Actions: Apple, Caterpillar
Apple (APL) rose 0.3% before publishing its results on Thursday. The technology giant based in Cupertino, California, introduced a new MacBook with the M3 chip. It is reported that the M3 Max high-end version is compatible with artificial intelligence developers.
Caterpillar (CAT) fell 6% after a sales outlook for slowing down offset a solid third quarter report.
Outside of the Dow Jones shares, Pinterest (PINS) shares rose and again exceeded the 50-day line after sales growth in the third quarter reached 11% and accelerated by a quarter-year. The most duplicated margins, reaching 24% compared to 11% last year. The action is in the purchase range from an entry at $28.90.
However, the leader of chips Latice semiconductor (LSSC) reported its fifth quarter of sales and profits slowdown. The actions fell to a minimum in November.
Rambus (RBMS) rose more than 10% as sales and revenues slowed for two consecutive quarters.
Wolfspeed (WOLF) also rose among the actions driven by the first fiscal quarter’s earnings reports. For its second quarter, the manufacturer of silicon fuel technologies expects sales at the average point of $207 million and a loss of 69 cents per action. The shares rose by 20%.
Tesla's actions rose after the manufacturer of electric vehicles won its first trial, in which it was claimed that his role as an automatic driver had caused fatal accidents.
Outside of Dow Jones: AMD rises before the gains
Also outside the Dow Jones index, the chip giant Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) climbed 0.2% before the gains, which were expected after the market closed. The actions are below their key mobile medium.
Cameco (CCJ), a recent addition to IBD SwingTrader, is recovering after playing its 50-day line with a strong volume. Sales in the third quarter of the uranium mining increased by 48 per cent, but the gains were 967 per cent.
In IBD 50, ELF (ELF) fell sharply below its 200-day line before Wednesday's earnings, but Deckers (DECK) showed impressive action and increased its solid earnings after the results report.

en.title: Indexes close up before key events

stories.body:
(Sharecast News) - US stocks closed higher on Tuesday as investors digested a flurry of data in a busy week for economic indicators, earnings and central bank action.
 At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 0.38% at 33,052.87, while the S&P 500 was 0.65% stronger at 4,193.80 and the Nasdaq Composite saw out the session 0.48% firmer at 12,851.24.
  The Dow closed 123.91 points higher on Tuesday as economic data came in mixed, with leading indicators very much in focus ahead of the two-day policy decision meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee which concludes on Wednesday.
  On the macro front, the Chicago manufacturing PMI fell from 44.1 to 44.0 in October, its 14th straight month below the 50-point level which separates contraction with expansion.
  Elsewhere, the Conference Board' s consumer confidence index fell to a five-month low of 102.6 this month, from a revised 104.3 in September, though above the 100 reading expected.
  Finally, the S&P/Case-Shiller home price index increased 2.6% year-on-year in August, after a 1% rise in July, with prices now at an all-time high. However, analysts at Oxford Economics said that prices will likely come under renewed pressure "given the steady climb in mortgage rates, which sat at a multi-decade high of nearly 8% as of last week.
  "Though the recent surge in bond yields will likely keep the Fed on hold at tomorrow's FOMC meeting, rate cuts are not on the immediate horizon, and a higher-for-longer approach from the Fed will keep mortgage rates elevated."
  In terms of earnings, Pinterest surged 19% as the photo-sharing app's third-quarter results beat expectations. Adjusted earnings rose 154% year-on-year to $0.28 a share, ahead of the $0.20 estimate.
  Drugmaker Pfizer fell was broadly flat after swinging to a worse-than-expected net loss of $2.38bn in the third quarter, compared with a net income of $8.61bn a year earlier.
  Caterpillar dropped 5% despite posting a jump in third-quarter profit amid solid demand for its high-end construction equipment in North America, while JetBlue Airways tanked as it cautioned that fourth-quarter losses would be wider than expected. Sector peers American United Delta and Southwest also fell.

Carlos R. Tartarini  Summary  Virtus Equity & Convertible Income Fund drops nearly 4% amidst broader market selloff.
 NIE relies on capital gains to cover its 10% annual distribution rate, which is challenging in the current high interest rate environment.
  NIE has outperformed the Morningstar US Moderate Aggressive Target Allocation benchmark but has not fully captured gains of its equity exposure.
  The broader selloff seen in the recent days has also hit shares of the Virtus Equity & Convertible Income Fund ( NYSE: NIE ), which dropped nearly 4% over this period, as investors continued to digest mixed earnings results and new macroeconomic indicators.
  The fund's tilt to growth stocks makes it certainly more volatile in a risk-averse environment. Meanwhile, it is fair to say that NIE is still delivering a total return of nearly 11% year-to-date.
  The flip side of it is that NIE relies mostly on capital gains to cover its annual distribution rate of roughly 10%. While stock appreciation in the fund's portfolio is likely to support such a distribution in the long run, the short-term outlook is challenging, as the high interest rate environment poses a challenge to growth stocks and current geopolitical tensions are certainly not helping for the time being.
  Fund Description & Highlights
  Having as the benchmarks the Russell 1000 Growth Index and the ICE BofA US Convertible Index, with a 60% / 40% allocation respectively, NIE is essentially a blended fund with investments in equities and convertible securities. Consistent with its growth-oriented equity exposure, the fund is largely focused on obtaining total return through capital appreciation and, to a lower extent, income from convertible securities and dividends.
  That is not to say that NIE does not offer a juicy distribution, on the contrary, NIE's annual distribution has yielded in the range of 6% to 8% over the last decade, and since 2022 distributions have been above 10% annually, without any distribution cuts over this period.
  This has a lot to do with the allocation strategy of the fund, as its overweight on higher growth companies have been quite favorable to the performance, since so-called growth stocks have largely outperformed the broader market during this time span.
  Nearly 61% of the fund was invested in equities as of September 29th, 2023. From the sector allocation perspective, the equity portfolio of NIE looks relatively close to the S&P 500 index, with information technology accounting for nearly 28.0% of total equities, consumer discretionary 17.7%, financials, 11.9%, healthcare 10.0%, industrials 9.5%, communication services 9.4%, energy 4.9%, utilities 3.5%, Materials 2.2%, Real Estate 1.6% and consumer staples 1.3%.
  The relevant distinctions relative to S&P 500 are the NIE's overweight allocation on consumer discretionary (+7.0%) and underweight exposure to healthcare (-3.4%) and consumer staples (-5.3%).
  Relative to the Russell 1000 Growth index though, NIE has a much more diversified allocation strategy, as the former is heavily concentrated on technology (51.0%) and has little exposure to financials (2.6%) and communication services (0.7%).
  As a result, S&P 500 seems a more appropriate benchmark for NIE, at least in terms of sector allocation.
  Looking at individual stocks' exposure, NIE's top six constituents are basically as same as S&P 500 and Russel 1000 Growth indexes (Alphabet ( GOOG GOOGL ), Microsoft ( MSFT ), Apple ( AAPL ), Amazon ( AMZN ), Tesla ( TSLA ), Nvidia ( NVDA )). On the other hand, NIE's top ten holdings account for nearly 40% of the equity side of the fund, while these top ten represent just 30% for S&P 500, but as much as 51% for Russell 1000 Growth index, due to its higher concentration on technology stocks.
  Overall, such differences in the stock exposure give the equity portion of NIE a compounded P/E Forward valuation at nearly 20.5 as of Sep 29th, 2023, compared to S&P 500's P/E Forward of 18 and Russell 1000 Growth index's P/E Forward of roughly 25.
  Of course, growth stocks are expected to trade at higher multiples, and the large exposure of Russell 1000 Growth index to the technology sector largely explains its higher P/E multiple. On the other hand, NIE's higher valuation relative to S&P 500 is consistent with NIE's overweight on consumer discretionary stocks, combined with its lower exposure to consumer staples, as discretionary stocks typically trade at higher multiples than consumer staples.
  In my view, NIE's overweight exposure to the consumer discretionary sector is a factor that can distinguish the fund from the broader S&P 500, as the consumer discretionary sector is expected to generate higher growth and share price returns to shareholders over time.
  As of Sep 29th 2023, the remaining of NIE's portfolio is comprised of convertible securities (34.4%) and cash and equivalents (4.7%). The vast majority of convertibles invested by the fund have maturity below 5 years and coupons ranging from 0% to 4%, with more than half of them being lower than 2%. This will result in a weighted coupon of 1.81%, which is below the 3% average of the category.
  Strong Performance In The Long Run
  There is no question that both equity indexes and convertibles have delivered a great total return performance over the past ten years, as illustrated below:
  As expected, NIE (blue line in the chart) is somewhere between the equity indexes and the convertible securities portfolio. For comparison purposes, the SPDR Bloomberg Convertible Securities ETF ( CWB ) was adopted as the benchmark for convertible securities.
  The following table shows the total return in different timeframes for NIE, equity indexes and CWB, as well as a hypothetical portfolio comprised by 60% of each equity index and 40% of convertibles.
  Despite the poor performance in the past month, we can see that NIE has outperformed the convertible securities benchmark, but has not been able to fully capture gains of the fund's equity exposure, as it has lagged the hypothetical 60/40 portfolio for both S&P 500 and Russell 100 Growth indexes, particularly over the 10-year period.
  To me, it is less of a concern, as the past decade was marked by low interest rates and extraordinary returns for growth stocks, and chances are that the environment for the next ten years or so is not going to be the same, at least in terms of the underlying interest rates for the most important economies in the world.
  However, overall, the combination of equities and securities applied by NIE has delivered consistent returns relative to another benchmark, the Morningstar US Moderate Aggressive Target Allocation NR USD, which seeks 77.5% exposure to global equity markets through a diversified mix of stocks and bonds. As we can see, NIE has handily outperformed the benchmark YTD and over the 10-year period as well.
  A Challenging Environment For NIE's Distributions
  Based on the dividend generated by equities of nearly 1.65% and the convertibles weighted coupon of 1.81%, the income produced by NIE's assets is somewhat modest for a fund with annual distributions of roughly 10%.
  For context, over the first six months of 2023, the fund generated $2.117 million through interest and $3.361 million through dividends as investment income. After netting out $3.304 million relative to net expenses during the period, net investment income was $2.171 million. Meanwhile, net realized gains from investments came in at $9.912 million and written options also produced a gain of 609 million.
  On the flip side, as the distribution in the period was $27.709 million, the fund had to cover it by returning capital to shareholders, using $15.017 million from unrealized appreciations. As these unrealized appreciations were $61.283 as of June 30th, 2023, it was not a major issue, and net assets increased by $46.266 or roughly $1.68 per common share.
  In August, the fund management maintained the quarterly distribution of $0.50 per common share, and declared it as return of capital as well. While remaining unrealized appreciations at roughly $1.18 per common share can still support another quarterly distribution at the end of the year, it seems to me that a special year-end distribution in the neighborhood of $1.70 to $1.90, as we have seen in the previous two years, is quite unlikely.
  As such, there is a good possibility that total distributions are limited to $0.50 per quarter, without any special distributions, until the stock market weakness persists, what will bring NIE's distribution rate back to the mid-single digit.
  The Price/NAV Discount Has Widened
  Following the recent broader market decline, the discount in shares of NIE over its Net Asset Value has just widened to 11.60%, a level that is reasonably below the 3-year average of -10.53%, reflecting the risk-off environment in the recent weeks. On the other hand, this discount is still above previous levels seen over the course of the year, when it dropped below -12%, as shown below.
  And while the price/NAV discount starts to become appealing, my view is that shares of NIE should remain particularly vulnerable until we see an improvement in stock market sentiment, as the fund relies on gains in its equity portfolio to support distributions, and changes in the distribution policy may cause the price/NAV discount to widen further
  That said, while I see NIE as an interesting fund to keep on the watchlist, as it combines equities and convertibles in just one investment vehicle, I rate NIE as a hold at the present moment due to current market environment and distribution headwinds.

sentences: Carlos R. Tartarini  Summary  Virtus Equity & Convertible Income Fund drops nearly 4% amidst broader market selloff.

Despite the poor performance in the past month, we can see that NIE has outperformed the convertible securities benchmark, but has not been able to fully capture gains of the fund's equity exposure, as it has lagged the hypothetical 60/40 portfolio for both S&P 500 and Russell 100 Growth indexes, particularly over the 10-year period.

And while the price/NAV discount starts to become appealing, my view is that shares of NIE should remain particularly vulnerable until we see an improvement in stock market sentiment, as the fund relies on gains in its equity portfolio to support distributions, and changes in the distribution policy may cause the price/NAV discount to widen further
  That said, while I see NIE as an interesting fund to keep on the watchlist, as it combines equities and convertibles in just one investment vehicle, I rate NIE as a hold at the present moment due to current market environment and distribution headwinds.

In my view, NIE's overweight exposure to the consumer discretionary sector is a factor that can distinguish the fund from the broader S&P 500, as the consumer discretionary sector is expected to generate higher growth and share price returns to shareholders over time.

On the other hand, NIE's top ten holdings account for nearly 40% of the equity side of the fund, while these top ten represent just 30% for S&P 500, but as much as 51% for Russell 1000 Growth index, due to its higher concentration on technology stocks.
